The paper proposes a memory architecture for autonomous learning and problem-solving, which suggests it could fall under the categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), and neural networks (cs.NE). The architecture is designed to support autonomous decision-making in robots, which could place it under the category of robotics (cs.RO). Finally, the paper also discusses the mathematical theory underlying the proposed architecture, which could make it relevant to the category of systems and control (cs.SY).
